# Credit Analyst – Investment Team

## Overview
Credit Analysts evaluate corporate bond issuers' creditworthiness through financial analysis, monitor portfolio holdings, and provide investment recommendations to Portfolio Managers at fixed income and credit fund managers.

## Core Responsibilities
- Analyze financial statements and build models to assess corporate bond issuers' creditworthiness through ratio analysis, peer comparisons, and scenario projections across diverse sectors.
- Evaluate new bond issuances by reviewing prospectuses, analyzing pricing and covenants, comparing to secondary alternatives, and providing timely investment recommendations to Portfolio Managers.
- Monitor existing portfolio holdings for credit deterioration by tracking financial results, news flow, bond price movements, and credit spreads to identify early warning signals and risks.
- Conduct sector and industry research by monitoring macroeconomic trends, regulatory changes, and competitive dynamics to maintain investment theses and identify sector-specific risks.
- Develop internal credit ratings and interpret rating agency reports, anticipating potential upgrades or downgrades while identifying where the fund's view diverges from agency assessments.
- Present credit research and recommendations to investment committees, collaborating with Portfolio Managers, traders, and risk management teams on portfolio strategy and positioning decisions.

## Key Skills Required

### Technical & Financial Analysis
- Advanced financial statement analysis, accounting knowledge, and complex Excel modeling capabilities
- Understanding of bond pricing, yield, duration, spread calculations, and various credit structures
- Credit metrics expertise including Debt/EBITDA, Interest Coverage, and Free Cash Flow/Debt ratios
- Bloomberg Terminal proficiency with functions like YAS, FA, DDIS, and ANR for market analysis

### Industry & Regulatory Knowledge
- Deep knowledge of 2-3 sectors developed over time with understanding of Australian business cycles
- APRA, ASIC, RBA, and ASX regulatory frameworks affecting issuers and credit markets
- Corporate finance concepts including capital structure, cost of capital, and valuation methodologies
- Covenant analysis skills to assess investor protections and security package quality

### Interpersonal & Professional Skills
- Clear written communication for credit memos distilling complex analysis into actionable insights
- Critical thinking to identify risks not apparent in financials and develop independent views
- Time management to prioritize multiple analyses and meet tight new issue deadlines (24-48 hours)
- Collaborative teamwork within investment structures and relationship building across departments

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (65-70%)
Deep-dive credit analysis building financial models and writing detailed memos, real-time market monitoring tracking Bloomberg news and bond prices, data gathering and organization, reading prospectuses and financial reports.

### Meetings and Collaboration (15-20%)
Morning investment team meetings covering market overview and new issues, credit committee discussions on recommendations, one-on-one Portfolio Manager debates on credit views, company management meetings for senior analysts.

### Market Events and Learning (10-15%)
Attending new issue roadshows by bond issuers (often virtual), participating in industry conferences and credit forums, professional development including CFA study and technical workshops, observing secondary market dynamics with traders.

### Portfolio Monitoring (Integrated throughout day)
Systematic watchlist reviews checking bonds with significant spread movements, updating credit watch spreadsheets, reviewing upcoming earnings calendars, flagging positions requiring closer scrutiny to Portfolio Managers.

### Ad-hoc Urgent Responses (Variable, time-sensitive)
Responding to trading desk queries about bond pricing, investigating unexpected spread widening or credit events, providing rapid commentary on breaking news affecting portfolio holdings, making fast-turnaround new issue decisions.

## Workplace Culture
Collaborative investment team environment with intellectual rigor, mentorship from senior analysts, deadline-driven during busy periods, reasonable work-life balance compared to banking though demanding.

## Career Path
- Entry: Credit Analyst (1-4 years, \$70k-\$110k base + 10-30% bonus)
- Progression: Senior Credit Analyst (4-6 years, \$110k-\$150k + 30-60% bonus) → Portfolio Manager/Head of Credit (6-10 years, \$150k-\$300k+ base + 50-100%+ bonus)

